item.title: Gold Rises Despite Dollar Strength
item.description: Gold futures edged higher in early London trading but concerns over the US. debt ceiling and possible default will create a floor for elevated prices until a resolution is found, Fitch said.

item.title: Nikkei Closes at 33-Year High; G-7 in Focus
item.description: The Nikkei closed up 0.8% at a 33-year high, with electronics stocks leading the gains, as optimism continues over progress in the U.S. debt-ceiling negotiations

item.title: U.S. 10-Year Treasury Yield's April Low of 3.253% Likely a Bottom
item.description: U.S. 10-year Treasury yield’s early April low of 3.253% was likely a bottom at least for the next 1-2 months, based on the daily chart, said UOB Global Economics & Markets Research.

item.title: German Bunds Could Benefit From Unlikely US Debt Ceiling Impasse
item.description: Citi said German Bunds would likely be a significant beneficiary of any debt ceiling impasse in the U.S. given the messy implications for Treasuries, but said the risk was small and falling.

item.title: UK Consumer Confidence Hits More-Than-Year High
item.description: Confidence among U.K. consumers improved for the fourth month in a row in May on signs of easing inflation and despite the squeeze on spending from higher interest rates.

item.title: Chinese Tech Giants' Results Reflect Lackluster Economic Recovery
item.description: Alibaba’s shares fell after revenue missed forecasts; Tencent and Baidu saw more marked upturn.

item.title: Fashion Giant Shein to Diversify Supply Chain Beyond China With Indian Fabrics
item.description: With the agreement, Shein is likely to source fabrics from small businesses in India, which could help the company diversify its supply chain beyond China.

item.title: Dollar Stays Close to Two-Month High as June Rate-Rise Chances Increase
item.description: The dollar edged lower in Europe on profit-taking after the DXY index hit a two-month high on Thursday, but UniCredit Research said the currency remained well-positioned to gain as markets are pricing some chance of a Fed rate rise in June.

item.title: Ukraine's Zelensky Expected to Travel to Japan for G-7 Summit
item.description: Russia’s invasion of Ukraine is slated to be a major focus of the gathering of world leaders in Hiroshima.

item.title: Greece's Leader Faces Elections Amid Rule-of-Law Concerns
item.description: A surveillance scandal has tarnished Kyriakos Mitsotakis’s standing as a liberal who vowed to repair Greece’s institutions.

item.title: Glynn's Take: RBNZ's Response to Government's Budget Could Be Swift and Harsh
item.description: The New Zealand government unveiled a generous increase in fiscal stimulus that could result in a harsh response by the country’s inflation-weary central bank as early as next week.

item.title: U.S. to Expand Sanctions, Export Controls on Russia
item.description: The new effort targets military and energy industries, with Western allies planning to roll out similar measures.

item.title: At Least 50 Car Models Tied to Potentially Explosive Air-Bag Part, WSJ Finds
item.description: Our analysis identified at least 6.8 million vehicles, spanning 15 automotive brands, with the potentially dangerous air-bag part that regulators are demanding be recalled. We’ve compiled a list of the affected makes and models, which includes brands such as Chevrolet, Ford and Hyundai.
